==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Plagal
<hw>Pla"gal</hw> <pr>(pl⟦amac⟧"g⟦ait⟧l)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F.,
from Gr. <grk>pla`gios</grk> sidewise, slanting.]</ety>
<fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>Having a scale running from the dominant to its
octave; -- said of certain old church modes or tunes, as opposed to
those called <contr>authentic</contr>, which ran from the tonic to its
octave.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Plagal cadence</b></col>, <cd>a cadence in which the
final chord on the tonic is preceded by the chord on the
subdominant.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plagate</ent>⟦br⟧
